I chose Market_Cap and Beta for the first cluster because I wanted to group the companies by their volatility and what the company is worth.

MC_Beta<-scale(MC_Beta)
distance<-get_dist(MC_Beta)
fviz_dist(distance)


I used the silhouette method to choose the optimal number of clusters.

fviz_nbclust(MC_Beta, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

k4<-kmeans(MC_Beta,centers=3,nstart = 25)
k4$centers
##   Market_Cap       Beta
## 1  -0.909057  1.4110965
## 2  -0.186420 -0.5286048
## 3   1.695581 -0.1780563
k4$size
## [1]  5 12  4
k4$cluster[18]
## [1] 2

As can be seen from the plot below the red cluster tends to have higher beta, but a low market cap. This means that these companies have more volatile stock, but a lower market capitalization. The majority of the companies fall in cluster 2, showing that they have close to average beta and market cap.

The only pattern, with respect to variables 10-12, from the clusters below is that cluster 3 companies are all either moderate buys or holds.

fviz_cluster(k4,data = MC_Beta)
